In July and August 2004, devastating floods in Bangladesh claimed over 700 lives and submerged 38% of the country, displacing millions.
The military is aiding in evacuations and relief efforts as major rivers overflow, affecting northern regions.
Monsoon rains and Himalayan snowmelt have marooned 200,000 people in the north.
The situation is expected to worsen as key rivers continue to rise.
The death toll has reached about 70 in India and Nepal, with millions displaced.
Efforts are underway to provide food, shelter, and medical aid to those affected, with international support from the UK.
